.TH HSH 1 "DECEMBER 2025" "Simple Shell" "HSH Manual"
.SH NAME
hsh \- Simple shell command interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a minimal Unix command-line interpreter that executes commands read from standard input or from a terminal. It is a project developed as part of the curriculum at Holberton School.

The shell works in two modes:
.IP \(bu 2
.B Interactive:
The shell displays a prompt (#cisboring$) and waits for user input.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Non-interactive:
The shell reads commands from a pipe (e.g., echo "ls" | ./hsh).

.SH FEATURES
.IP \(bu 2
Finding commands in the 
.B PATH
variable.
.IP \(bu 2
Executing commands with their arguments.
.IP \(bu 2
Handling the 
.B Ctrl+D 
(EOF) to exit the shell.
.IP \(bu 2
Handling 
.B Ctrl+C 
(SIGINT) to prevent exiting.

.SH BUILT-INS
The following commands are built directly into the shell:
.TP
.B exit
Terminates the shell process.
.TP
.B env
Prints all the environment variables in the current session.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.B hsh
returns the status of the last command executed. If a command is not found, it returns 127.

.SH EXAMPLES
To start the shell:
.nf
    $ ./hsh
.fi

To run a command with arguments:
.nf
    #cisboring$ /bin/ls -l /tmp
.fi

To exit the shell:
.nf
    #cisboring$ exit
.fi

.SH BUGS
No known bugs. Please report any issues.

